<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
I'm not sure it's even POSSIBLE to hope that all item changes will benefit the player. This by virtue of the fact some changes will be seen as a negative by some, positive by others.<P>I however do feel deeply for those that went into VP, got hammered, an came back out little to show for it. Complaints were made, fixes performed, an presto... Problem is "solved" but those that brought it up sit with the "orginal" crud. That's all well an good, to adhere to this "fair" two way street attempt at item replacement policy. I see it in another light. I see it as although they have "fixed" the problem, in turn the insufficiently rewarded pioneers payed double price, for half pay.<P>Granted in this case, it's perhaps not something VI could have seen with their current methods of "play testing" if you can call it that. I fail to see why some arrangement couldn't have been offered to those instrumental in getting this ironed out. Gordon was quick to retort with "we'll we're letting you keep your nifty uber loot stuff.." (that's not verbatim from him but gist with perhaps some bias). Yeah well an good Gordon, but it looks as sounds to me more like simply generated exuse version 5.0.1 to deal with something. Would it have been hugely intensive to say, offer to upgrade their current under par items, acknowledged so with the needed fix? Would it have put a wrench in those furiously churning gears of progress in VI to have made the offer?<P>Had they turned it down, you have your current situation under their choice. Your problem is solved, they keep their crud, you don't have to bother with the "junk". Had they taken the offer, you swap out their crud for the enhanced, they hand over the uber loot deemed inappropriate. Yes, I know, it can all be so darned complicated.<P>Pfiles...yep, that P word. Shouldn't be overly hard to see who has what, if the info is already there eh? I'll stop here before I get totally off topic. I will say it must be nice be'n able to sit on a fence an waffle for a live'n. Sorry, I'd be less biased, shall we say, an more even minded about the whole. It's just that darn stellar track record VI has with it's customer base.<P> <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR>Originally posted by Kivlan:<BR><B>Recently Gordon made a statement regarding how they had to be consistant with previous enhancements/drop changes. (Read <A HREF="http://eq.castersrealm.com/viewarticle.asp?Article=2738" TARGET=_blank>http://eq.castersrealm.com/viewarticle.asp?Article=2738</A>  for more information) What is your opinion on this? Should loot changes always benefit the player, or should they stay consistant with their "no item change" policy, even if the change would benefit players? Post your thoughts here.</B><HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P>
