It is about numbers period.  When I log on to play on a server with 2000 players for my 3 hour stint, I am actually sharing my playing time with around 10000 characters.  <P>Everquest is specifically built for those who can play more(often/longer times).  They are allowed to form guilds and they get all 8 of their characters to high levels by power leveling.<P>I can't believe I pay my $10 to have my prey/all decent xp/loot prey/etc.. stolen by guilds so they can power level/twink their characters.  Being told by guides/gms even though I am paying for a service, the service doesn't cater to individual players.  I love it when the same guides/gms tell me to go level elsewhere and let guilds do what they want since they are following "the spirit" of the game by grouping and interacting.  I love it when I spend my 3 hours running zone to zone asking to group up and seeing guilds hog/ks every good spawn.  I love it how if you have an adverse interaction with a "guild official/founder" you are on a "black list" and wont be able to join groups that have guild members in them.<P>If Verant really wants to (use their term) balance the game out then take away 6 character slots on each server.  Yes if you allow only 2 character slots(primary and alternate) alot of the farmers will go away, the uber guilds will stop getting in the casual players way and focus on elevating their primary characters to 60, and the result will be there will be more prey for the casual player to hunt, beter chances of getting good loot at the right level, and less level 1 twinks in full crafted/yaks killing everything and being an ass while doing it. <P>Since Verant refuses to put game information in the game where it belongs and relies on websites(which they publically denounce), another idea is have the character gather information about its class(what spells do, pet commands, spell lists, class guild quests(the name is everquest not forever looking for quests or evercamp correct?), learning new languages, improving secondary skills, etc...  This is the first rpg where I had no clue what my character(s) stats/skills/spells meant or what effect(s) they have upon start up. <P>Sorry that I ranted. There is just too much little stuff wrong with EQ to really enjoy it to its fullest extent.<P>Haqueim<BR>Wandering Mage
